\section{Introduction}
The purpose of this note is to describe a small modal type theory in which we can do a little bit of internalized
parametricity. It is not a goal to do iterated internalized parametricity. It {\em is} a goal to have the type system
in some sense ``tell us itself'' what parametricity means for each type in it. That is, we aim to set up judgments
and types and intro and elim rules in such a way that various type isomorphisms arise as emergent facts.
So instead of {\em defining} that a value $f : A \to B$ ``belongs to the logical relation'' at type $A \to B$ if and
only if for every $a : A$ which belongs to the relation at type $A$ we have that $f\ a$ belongs to the relation
at type $B$, we are able to construct this as a term internally in the system.

We avoid introducing an explicit interval object. We avoid introducing any computational principles
that are divorced from any particular logical-connective/type-former.

One pervasive intuition that is helpful to lean on is that we are, in this theory,
``programming in the presheaf category $\rtype^{\bf 2}$'', where $\bf 2$ is the category
with two objects and one trivial morphism.

\section{Language}


The type theory is modal, and we have several sorts of variables in the context.
Variables may be ordinary $x : A$, strong $x :: A$, or weak $x \div A$.
There is also a pseudo-variable $\star$, with no variable name.
 The `explosion' context
 $\emptyset$ can be thought of as if it were any context with a $0$ variable in it; it is intrinsically contradictory.


\[\begin{tabular}{rccl}
  Contexts&$\Gamma$&$::=$&$\cdot  \celse \Gamma, x : A \celse \Gamma, x :: A \celse \Gamma, x \div A$\\
  Low Contexts&$\bar\Gamma$&$::=$&$\cdot \celse \Gamma, x : A \celse \Gamma, x :: A $\\
  Types&$A$&$::=$&$\cdots \celse D \bar A   \celse \pp {\bar M} A\celse \gg (x : \bar A) . \bar B $\\
  Low Types&$\bar A$&$::=$&$\cdots \celse \lax A \celse \surd A $\\
  Terms&$M$&$::=$&$\cdots \celse  \ilax M \celse \elax M \celse \isurd M \celse \esurd M \celse \iblat M \celse \eblat M$\\
&&&$\qquad \{M\} \celse \epair M N \celse \mpair M N \celse M.1 \celse M.2  $\\
Low  Terms&$\bar M$&$::=$&$\cdots \celse  \ilax M \celse \elax M \celse \isurd M \celse \esurd M \celse \iblat M \celse \eblat M$\\
&&&$\qquad \{M\} \celse \epair M N \celse \mpair M N \celse M.1 \celse M.2  $\\
\end{tabular}\]

\subsection{Operations}
We define two operations on contexts, {\em promotion} $\dash^\oplus$, and ${\em demotion}$ $\dash^\ominus$.
Both operations take a context and produce a context. The main action of interest is on ordinary variables:
promotion turns them into strong variables, demotion turns them into weak variables. Promotion `explodes'
if it encounters $\star$, whereas demotion simply deletes it.
\[\begin{tabular}{rcl}
 $ (\Gamma, x : A)^\oplus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\oplus, x :: A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, x :: A)^\oplus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\oplus, x :: A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, x \div A)^\oplus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\oplus, x \div A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, \star)^\oplus$&$:=$&$\emptyset$\\
 $ (\emptyset)^\oplus$&$:=$&$\emptyset$\\
 $ (\cdot)^\oplus$&$:=$&$\cdot$\\
\end{tabular}
\qquad
\begin{tabular}{rcl}
 $ (\Gamma, x : A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\ominus, x \div A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, x :: A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\ominus, x :: A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, x \div A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\ominus, x \div A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, \star)^\ominus$&$:=$&$\Gamma^\ominus$\\
 $ (\emptyset)^\ominus$&$:=$&$\emptyset$\\
 $ (\cdot)^\ominus$&$:=$&$\cdot$\\
\end{tabular}\]

\subsection{Semantics}
Syntactically, we define some operations $\dash^*$ and $\sem\dash$ and $\tsem\dash\dash$ so that:

\begin{tabular}{l}
If $\Gamma$ is a context, then ${\Gamma}^*$ is a context.\\
If $A$ is a type, then ${A}^*$ is a type.\\
If $M$ is a term, then ${M}^*$ is a term.
If $\Gamma$ is a context, then $\sem{\Gamma}$ is a context.\\
If $A$ is a type and $M^*$ is a term, then $\tsem A {M^*}$ is a type.\\
If $M$ is a term, then $\sem{M}$ is a term.
\end{tabular}

Furthermore we wish to prove that these operations preserve typing:

\begin{tabular}{l}
If $\prov \Gamma\rctx$, then $\prov {\Gamma}^*\rctx$.\\
If $\Gamma \prov A : \rtype$, then $\Gamma^* \prov A^* : \rtype$.\\
If $\Gamma \prov M : A$, then $\Gamma^* \prov M^* : {A}^*$.\\
If $\prov \Gamma\rctx$, then $\prov \sem{\Gamma}\rctx$.\\
If $\Gamma \prov A : \rtype$, then $\sem \Gamma, x : A^* \prov \tsem A x : \rtype$.\\
If $\Gamma \prov M : A$, then $\sem\Gamma \prov \sem M : \tsem A {M^*}$\\
\end{tabular}
\subsection{Rules}

\subsubsection{Context Formation}
These are the rules for well-formed contexts. The type of a strong variable
is typed in the demotion of the context to its left. The type of a weak variable
is typed in the context to its left augmented with a $\star$.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\justifies
\prov \cdot \rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\justifies
\prov \emptyset \rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x : A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x :: A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma, \star \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x \div A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, \star )\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]

Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
(\Gamma, x : A)^* &=& (\Gamma^*, x^* : A^*)\\
(\Gamma, x :: A)^* &=& (\Gamma^*, x^* : A^*, \sem x : \tsem A {M^*})\\
(\Gamma, x \div A)^* &=& (\Gamma^*, x^* : A^*)\\
(\Gamma, \star)^* &=& \Gamma^*\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\sem{\Gamma, x : A} &=& (\sem\Gamma, x^* : A^*, \sem x : \tsem A {M^*})\\
\sem{\Gamma, x :: A} &=& (\sem\Gamma, x^* : A^*, \sem x : \tsem A {M^*})\\
\sem{\Gamma, x \div A} &=& (\sem\Gamma, x^* : A^*)\\
\sem{\Gamma, \star} &=& \alpha : 0\\
\end{array}\]
\subsubsection{Variable Rules}
We can use strong or ordinary variables whenever they are in the context.
Weak variables require that a $\star$ is present in the context for them to be used;
$\star$ acts like a key that unlocks them. Weak variables are essentially the locked
part of the context in the sense of MTT.

One might reasonably ask why it is that strong and ordinary variables appear to behave identically here;
the answer is that the difference between them lies in how they respond to demotion. Strong variables
remain strong after demotion, but ordinary variables do not.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
x : A \in  \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
x :: A \in  \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
x \div A \in  \Gamma \qquad \star \in \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
\subsection{Type Formers}
\subsubsection{The Fiber Type}
The type $\pp M A$ represents the `fiber over $M$ in the map in the arrow category' or
`the proofs that $M$ belongs to the logical relation'
or `the proofs that $M$ is a good, special, nice, parametric element of the type $A$'.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype \quad \Gamma, \star \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \pp M A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\quad
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma^\ominus \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \{M\} : \pp M A
\end{prooftree}
\quad
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma,\star \prov M : A \quad \Gamma^\oplus, \star \prov N : \pp M A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \epair M N : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
We can also think of the introduction type as something like
\[\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma^\ominus \prov M : A \qquad \Gamma, \star \prov M \equiv N
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \{M\} : \pp N A
\end{prooftree}
\]
because $M$ can be weakened to the context $\Gamma, \star$, and more definitional
equalities hold under $\star$.

Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{\pp M A}^* &=& \tsem A {M^*}\\
\{M\}^* &=& \sem M\\
(\epair M N)^* &=& M^*\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{\pp M A}\_ &=& 1\\
\{M\}^* &=& \langle\rangle\\
\sem{\epair M N} &=& N^*\\
\end{array}\]
\subsubsection{The Open Modality}
The modality $\lax$ can be thought of as the functor from $\rtype^{\bf 2}$ to itself that takes
any function $f : A \to B$ and returns the identity $B \to B$. To apply $\lax$ is to `move to unique the future world'
or `go downstairs' if we think of $A$ lying above $B$, and to forget everything we knew about the upstairs data.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma, \star \prov  A : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \lax A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma, \star \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \ilax M  : \lax A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma \prov M : \lax A\qquad \star \in \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \elax M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{(\lax A)}^* &=&  A^*\\
(\ilax M)^* &=& M^*\\
(\elax M)^* &=& M^*\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{\lax A}\_ &=& 1\\
\sem{\ilax M} &=& \langle\rangle\\
\sem{\elax M} &=& \babort(\alpha)\\
\end{array}\]

\subsubsection{The Square Root Modality}
The modality $\surd$ can be thought of as the functor from $\rtype^{\bf 2}$ to itself that takes
any function $f : A \to B$ and returns the identity $A \to A$. To apply $\surd$ is to `retreat to the past world'
or `go upstairs', i.e. replace the data `downstairs' with the points that were formerly available upstairs.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \surd A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\ominus \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \isurd M  : \surd A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma, \star \prov M : \surd A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \esurd M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{(\surd A)}^* &=&  (x : A^*) \x \tsem A x\\
(\isurd M)^* &=& \pair {M^*} {\sem M}\\
(\esurd M)^* &=& (M^*).1\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{\surd A}\_ &=& 1\\
\sem{\isurd M} &=& \langle\rangle\\
\sem{\esurd M} &=& (M^*).2\\
\end{array}\]

\subsubsection{The Closed Modality}
The modality $\blat$ can be thought of as the functor from $\rtype^{\bf 2}$ to itself that takes
any function $f : A \to B$ and returns the unique map $A \to 1$. To apply $\blat$ is to destroy all distinctions
we formerly made `downstairs', while retaining all `upstairs' data.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\oplus \prov  A : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \blat A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\oplus \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \iblat M  : \blat A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\ominus \prov M : \blat A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \eblat M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{(\blat A)}^* &=& 1\\
(\iblat M)^* &=& \langle\rangle\\
(\eblat M)^* &=& \sem M.1\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{\blat A}\_ &=&  (x : A^*) \x \tsem A x\\
\sem{\iblat M} &=& \pair {M^*} {\sem M}\\
\sem{\eblat M} &=& \sem M.2\\
\end{array}\]

\subsubsection{The Glue Type}
The glue type takes specifications of a `downstairs' and `upstairs' type and glues them together.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma, \star \prov A : \rtype \qquad \Gamma^\oplus, \star, x : A\prov B : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \gg(x : A) . B : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma, \star \prov M : A  \qquad \Gamma^\oplus, \star \prov N : [M/x]B
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \mpair M N : \gg(x : A) . B : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma \prov  M : \gg(x : A) . B
\justifies
\Gamma, \star \prov M.1 : A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma \prov  M : \gg(x : A) . B
\justifies
  \Gamma^\oplus, \star\prov M.2 : [M.1/x]B
\end{prooftree}
\]

Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{( \gg(x : A) . B)}^* &=& A^*\\
\mpair M N ^* &=& M^*\\
(M.1)^* &=&  M^*\\
(M.2)^* &=& \sem M\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{ \gg(x : A) . B} {M^*} &=&  [M^*/x^*]B^*\\
\sem{ \mpair M N } &=& N^*\\
\sem{M.1} &=& \babort(\alpha)\\
\sem{M.2} &=& \babort(\alpha)\\
\end{array}\]

\section{Interesting Theorems}

\subsection{The Nondependent Function Type}
If
\[ \prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov B : \rtype \qquad
\Gamma, \star \prov f : A \to B\]
then there exists an explicit isomorphism
\[\Gamma \prov \pp f {A \to B}  \cong (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B \]
Explicitly, here is the construction:
\[ \Gamma \prov \mathsf{fore} : (f' : \pp f {A \to B}) (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B \]
\[\mathsf{fore} = \lambda f'.\lambda a.\lambda a'.  \{(\epair f {f'})\ (\epair { a} {a'})\}\]
\[ \Gamma \prov \mathsf{back} : (k : (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B) \to \pp f {A \to B} \]
\[\mathsf{back} = \lambda k. \{\lambda x . (\epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}})\}\]
Let's typecheck these. Make some abbreviations
\[\Gamma_1 = (\Gamma^\ominus, f' \div \pp f {A \to B}, a \div  A, a' \div \pp { a} A) \]
\[\Gamma_2 = ( \Gamma^\ominus, k \div (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B)\]
\[\Gamma_3 = (\Gamma_2, x :: A, \star)\]
and see
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_1, \star \prov f  :  A \to B
\]
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_1, \star \prov f' :  \pp f {A \to B}
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_1 \prov \epair f {f'} :  A \to B
\]
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_1, \star \prov { a}  :  A
\]
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_1, \star \prov a' :  \pp { a} A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_1 \prov \epair { a} {a'} :  A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_1 \prov (\epair f {f'})\ (\epair { a} {a'}) :  B
\]
\justifies
\Gamma, f' : \pp f {A \to B}, a :  A, a' : \pp { a} A \prov \{(\epair f {f'})\ (\epair { a} {a'})\} : \pp {f\ a} B
\end{prooftree}
\]
checking as a side condition that
\[ (\epair f {f'})\ (\epair { a} {a'})\equiv_\star f\ a\]
and then
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  k : (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B
\]
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  x : A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  {k\ x} : \pp x A \to  \pp {f\ x} B
\]
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  x :  A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  {\{x\}} : \pp x A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  {k\ x\ \{x\}} : \pp {f\ x} B
\end{prooftree}
\]
can be inserted into
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
\[
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_2, x : A, \star \prov f : A \to B
\]
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_2, x : A, \star \prov x : A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_2, x : A, \star \prov f\ x : B
\]
\qquad
{\vdots \atop \Gamma_3 \prov  {k\ x\ \{x\}} : \pp {f\ x} B}
\justifies
\Gamma_2, x : A \prov \epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}} : B
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_2 \prov \lambda x . (\epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}}) : A \to B
\]
\justifies
\Gamma, k : (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B) \prov \{\lambda x . (\epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}})\} : \pp f {A \to B}
\end{prooftree}
\]
checking as a side condition that
\[ \lambda x . (\epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}}) \equiv_\star f\]

\subsection{The Dependent Function Type}
This is very similar to the non-dependent case. The difference is we must substitute into $B$.
If
\[ \prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype \qquad \Gamma^\ominus, x : A \prov B : \rtype \qquad
\Gamma, \star \prov f : (x : A) \to B\]
then there exists an explicit isomorphism
\[\Gamma \prov \pp f {(x : A) \to B}  \cong (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} {[\epair a {a'} / x]B} \]

